\margl1224\margr1224\margt1037\margb936
\pard\qc\sb380\sa110\cf1\fs44 Question Serving Logic\cf0\par
\pard\qc\sb0\sa360\fs22 Diagnostic App - Simple Explanation\cf0\par
\pard\sb220\sa80\cf1\b\fs30 Short Answer\b0\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa120\fs21 The app does not randomly pick questions one by one. It first finds all questions that match the selected subject, class, and topic. Then it builds a balanced test using learning objective coverage, difficulty balance, question type variety, and the questions available in the database.\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa120\fs21 If the perfect balance is not possible because there are not enough questions, the app fills the remaining slots with the best available questions.\cf0\par
\pard\sb140\sa70\b\fs21 Test Type        Total Questions        Difficulty Target\b0\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa40\fs21 Topic Test      18                     6 easy, 6 medium, 6 hard\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa160\fs21 Grade Test      22                     5 easy, 7 medium, 10 hard\cf0\par
\pard\sb220\sa80\cf1\b\fs30 Topic Test\b0\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa120\fs21 A topic test serves up to 18 questions. The intended difficulty ratio is equal across all three levels:\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa55\fs21 - 6 easy questions\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa55\fs21 - 6 medium questions\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa55\fs21 - 6 hard questions\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa120\fs21 In simple terms: Easy : Medium : Hard = 1 : 1 : 1.\cf0\par
\pard\sb180\sa70\cf2\b\fs24 How Learning Objectives Are Selected\b0\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa120\fs21 The learning objectives are not separately selected by the user. They come from the questions available for the selected topic.\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa120\fs21 For example, if a topic has questions from 5 learning objectives, the app tries to spread the test across those objectives.\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa120\fs21 It uses a round-robin style:\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa55\fs21 1. Pick one question from learning objective A.\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa55\fs21 2. Pick one question from learning objective B.\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa55\fs21 3. Pick one question from learning objective C.\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa55\fs21 4. Continue cycling through the learning objectives.\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa120\fs21 This prevents the test from asking too many questions from only one learning objective.\cf0\par
\pard\sb180\sa70\cf2\b\fs24 Interactive Question Target\b0\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa120\fs21 The app tries to include interactive question types such as fill in the blank and drag and drop.\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa120\fs21 The target is around one-third of the test. For an 18-question topic test, that means around 6 interactive questions, if enough are available.\cf0\par
\page
\pard\sb180\sa70\cf2\b\fs24 What Happens If Questions Are Missing\b0\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa120\fs21 If the app cannot find enough questions for a difficulty level or learning objective, it does not fail immediately. It fills the remaining slots using available questions from other difficulty levels or objectives.\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa120\fs21 Example: if the app wants 6 hard questions but only 4 hard questions exist, it uses those 4 and fills the remaining 2 slots from other available questions.\cf0\par
\pard\sb220\sa80\cf1\b\fs30 Grade Test\b0\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa120\fs21 A grade test serves up to 22 questions. The target difficulty split is:\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa55\fs21 - 5 easy questions\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa55\fs21 - 7 medium questions\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa55\fs21 - 10 hard questions\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa120\fs21 So the grade test is slightly more challenge-heavy than the topic test.\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa120\fs21 Instead of balancing mainly by learning objective, the grade test balances more by topic, because it checks the broader class-level syllabus.\cf0\par
\pard\sb220\sa80\cf1\b\fs30 Final Question Order\b0\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa120\fs21 After the questions are selected, the app mixes question types so the student does not see too many questions of the same format back-to-back.\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa120\fs21 For example, instead of showing MCQ, MCQ, MCQ, MCQ, it tries to mix formats like MCQ, fill in the blank, drag and drop, MCQ, and short answer.\cf0\par
\pard\sb220\sa80\cf1\b\fs30 In Plain Language\b0\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa120\fs21 The app is trying to create a fair diagnostic test.\cf0\par
\pard\sb180\sa70\cf2\b\fs24 For a topic test, it wants:\b0\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa55\fs21 - 18 questions\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa55\fs21 - equal easy, medium, and hard coverage\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa55\fs21 - questions spread across learning objectives\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa55\fs21 - some interactive questions\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa55\fs21 - mixed question formats\cf0\par
\pard\sb180\sa70\cf2\b\fs24 For a grade test, it wants:\b0\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa55\fs21 - 22 questions\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa55\fs21 - more hard questions than easy questions\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa55\fs21 - questions spread across topics\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa55\fs21 - some interactive questions\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa55\fs21 - mixed question formats\cf0\par
\pard\sb0\sa120\fs21 The final test depends on what questions actually exist in the database.\cf0\par
\pard\sb160\sa120\cf1\fs18 Code references: lib/quiz-counts.ts; agents/diagnostic/tools/contentQuiz.ts for difficulty targets, round-robin selection, and question type mixing.\cf0\par
}